# Force LF in the working tree on every platform.
#
# Why a catch-all: the conformity pack's promise is a byte-for-byte
# rebuild. The compiler emits the artefacts (manifest.json, the two
# SBOMs, vex, provenance) with LF newlines on every OS, so the only way
# a regenerated set can differ from a committed snapshot is if a
# checkout rewrote committed LF to CRLF. A checkout with
# core.autocrlf=true does exactly that to any text file not pinned here.
# Pinning every tracked file to eol=lf makes the working tree LF
# regardless of the contributor's autocrlf setting, so:
#   - main.capa hashes the same bytes the CI sees, and
#   - if you opt into committing an artefact snapshot (see .gitignore),
#     that snapshot stays reproducible across operating systems.
#
# Every tracked file in this repo is text (.capa, .json, .md, .toml,
# LICENSE); there are no binaries, so a blanket eol=lf is safe. If a
# binary asset is ever added, give it an explicit `*.ext binary` rule
# below to opt it out.
* text=auto eol=lf
